<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="2" pageNumber="74" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1692,2043]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1436,151,321]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="2" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1800,1826]" pageId="2" pageNumber="74">Discussion:</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[395,493,1800,1826]" pageId="2" pageNumber="74">holotype</typeStatus>
is a male and encrusted with what appear to be mineral deposits (
<figureCitation box="[1256,1323,1800,1826]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1036,1060]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,342,1010]" captionTargetId="figure-85@3.[151,1435,342,1010]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Cryphocricos barozzii (1) holotype, (2) brachypterous female from Rosario River, Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil, (3) abdominal terga showing dark tubercles near middle of III–V, (4) subgenital plate of two specimens from Nova Teutonia, Brazil showing intrapopulational variation in shape of posterior margin. Figure 1 courtesy of NHMW Hemiptera Image Collection / Harald Bruckner and Herbert Zettel." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4693075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4693075/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="74">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Parsons, M. C. &amp; Hewson, R. J." pageId="2" pageNumber="74" pagination="510 - 527" refId="ref13384" refString="Parsons, M. C. &amp; Hewson, R. J. (1974) Plastral respiratory devices in adult Cryphocricos (Naucoridae: Heteroptera). Psyche, 81, 510 - 527. https: // doi. org / 10.1155 / 1974 / 30691" type="journal article" year="1974">Parsons &amp; Hewson (1974)</bibRefCitation>
used 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Montandon" authorityYear="1897" box="[421,543,1836,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryptocricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barozzii">
<emphasis box="[421,543,1836,1862]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="74">C. barozzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Usinger" authorityYear="1947" box="[598,764,1836,1862]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryphocricos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hungerfordi">
<emphasis box="[598,764,1836,1862]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="74">C. hungerfordi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to study the morphology of the cuticle showing its plastron retention capability. Further, 
<bibRefCitation author="Parsons, M. C." box="[479,648,1872,1899]" pageId="2" pageNumber="74" pagination="119 - 151" refId="ref13432" refString="Parsons, M. C. (1966) Studies on the cephalic anatomy of Naucoridae (Heteroptera). Transactions of the Royal Entomological Society of London, 118 (5), 119 - 151. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1966. tb 00836. x" type="journal article" year="1966">Parsons (1966)</bibRefCitation>
provided a comparative analysis of the cephalic anatomy among five genera of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Leach" baseAuthorityYear="1815" box="[266,395,1908,1934]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Naucoridae</taxonomicName>
and one of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1851" box="[531,720,1908,1934]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelocheiridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Aphelocheiridae</taxonomicName>
. Later, Parsons (1974) studied the morphology of the pterothoracic intersegmental region including that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Montandon" authorityYear="1897" box="[648,769,1944,1970]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryptocricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barozzii">
<emphasis box="[648,769,1944,1970]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="74">C. barozzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez Ruf, M. L. &amp; Pellerano, G. N. &amp; Bachmann, A. O." box="[782,1041,1944,1971]" pageId="2" pageNumber="74" pagination="267 - 273" refId="ref13183" refString="Lopez Ruf, M. L., Pellerano, G. N. &amp; Bachmann, A. O. (2000) Ventilatory structures in Cryphocricos barozzii Signoret (Heteroptera, Naucoroidea). Revista Brasileira de Biologia, 60 (2), 267 - 273. https: // doi. org / 10.1590 / S 0034 - 71082000000200010" type="journal article" year="2000">
Lopez Ruf 
<emphasis box="[906,961,1944,1970]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="74">et al.</emphasis>
(2000)
</bibRefCitation>
described the ventilatory structures of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Montandon" authorityYear="1897" box="[183,306,1980,2006]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryptocricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barozzii">
<emphasis box="[183,306,1980,2006]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="74">C. barozzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and compared them to those of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fabricius, 1794)" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1794" box="[675,1156,1980,2006]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelocheiridae" genus="Aphelocheirus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aestivalis">
<emphasis box="[675,951,1980,2006]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="74">Aphelocheirus aestivalis</emphasis>
(Fabricius, 1794)
</taxonomicName>
. They suggested the two genera are more closely related than previously thought because the specialized plastron system could not have evolved convergently. However, a molecular phylogeny of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Montandon" authorityYear="1897" box="[810,983,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Cryphocricinae">Cryphocricinae</taxonomicName>
(Reynoso-Velasco &amp; Sites, in prep.) and upcoming phylogeny of the entire family by RWS indicate the opposite, that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1851" box="[1040,1225,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Aphelocheiridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Aphelocheiridae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1850" box="[1284,1436,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryphocricos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1284,1436,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">Cryphocricos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(and most likely the Papuan genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Montandon" authorityYear="1897" box="[539,646,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Idiocarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[539,646,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">Idiocarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) evolved plastron systems convergently. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Montandon" authorityYear="1897" box="[1105,1212,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Idiocarus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1105,1212,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">Idiocarus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has not been shown to have plastral respiration, although it lives in fast, highly oxygenated streams and has alary dimorphism with the brachypterous form predominant.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4693075" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4693075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4693075/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" startId="3.[151,264,1036,1060]" targetBox="[151,1435,342,1010]" targetPageId="3">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1036,1168]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,315,1036,1060]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">FIGURES 1–4.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1850" box="[322,547,1036,1060]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryphocricos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barozzii">
<emphasis box="[322,547,1036,1060]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">Cryphocricos barozzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(1) holotype, (2) brachypterous female from Rosario River, Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil, (3) abdominal terga showing dark tubercles near middle of III–V, (4) subgenital plate of two specimens from Nova Teutonia, Brazil showing intrapopulational variation in shape of posterior margin. Figure 1 courtesy of NHMW 
<taxonomicName authority="Image" authorityName="Image" box="[1180,1355,1108,1132]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Hemiptera Image</taxonomicName>
Collection / Harald Bruckner and Herbert Zettel.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1214,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">
In a treatment of species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1850" box="[511,663,1214,1240]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryphocricos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[511,663,1214,1240]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">Cryphocricos</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known or thought to occur in 
<collectingCountry box="[1003,1117,1214,1240]" name="Argentina" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez Ruf, M. L." box="[1129,1329,1214,1241]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" pagination="103 - 120" refId="ref13109" refString="Lopez Ruf, M. L. (1991) El genero Cryphocricos en la Argentina (Hemiptera-Limnocoridae). Revista de la Sociedad Entomologica Argentina, 49 (1 - 4), 103 - 120." type="journal article" year="1991">Lopez Ruf (1991)</bibRefCitation>
provided a detailed diagnosis for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1850" box="[420,542,1250,1277]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryphocricos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barozzii">
<emphasis box="[420,542,1250,1277]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">C. barozzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and descriptions of nymphal instars 1–3 and 5 and later revised her description of instar 3 (
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez Ruf, M. L." box="[281,470,1286,1313]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" pagination="120 - 121" refId="ref13147" refString="Lopez Ruf, M. L. (1996) Nuevas consideraciones sobre Cryphocricos barozzii Signoret y descripcion de la ninfa III (Insecta- Heteroptera-Limnocoridae). Physis, B 51, 120 - 121." type="journal article" year="1996">Lopez Ruf 1996</bibRefCitation>
). Because she could not locate the 
<typeStatus box="[865,916,1287,1313]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">type</typeStatus>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Lopez Ruf, M. L." box="[928,1129,1286,1313]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" pagination="103 - 120" refId="ref13109" refString="Lopez Ruf, M. L. (1991) El genero Cryphocricos en la Argentina (Hemiptera-Limnocoridae). Revista de la Sociedad Entomologica Argentina, 49 (1 - 4), 103 - 120." type="journal article" year="1991">Lopez Ruf (1991)</bibRefCitation>
based her identification on comparison of the curvature of the lateral margins of her specimens with that in a drawing by 
<bibRefCitation author="Signoret, V." box="[1180,1359,1322,1349]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" pagination="289 - 291" refId="ref13706" refString="Signoret, V. (1850) Description d'un genre nouveau de l'ordre des Hemipteres Heteropteres, et de la section des Hydrocoryses. Revue et magasin de zoologie pure et appliquee, 2, 289 - 291." type="journal article" year="1850">Signoret (1850)</bibRefCitation>
. I have not seen a drawing in the original description by 
<bibRefCitation author="Signoret, V." box="[698,877,1358,1385]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" pagination="289 - 291" refId="ref13706" refString="Signoret, V. (1850) Description d'un genre nouveau de l'ordre des Hemipteres Heteropteres, et de la section des Hydrocoryses. Revue et magasin de zoologie pure et appliquee, 2, 289 - 291." type="journal article" year="1850">Signoret (1850)</bibRefCitation>
, but if it exists, his rendering of the lateral margin cannot be considered a reliable diagnostic characteristic by which to distinguish 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1850" box="[1080,1204,1394,1421]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryphocricos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barozzii">
<emphasis box="[1080,1204,1394,1421]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">C. barozzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from all congeners; thus, the descriptive information in this paper should be considered suspect unless validated by the examination of vouchers.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="76" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1214,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,1502,1528]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
The original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Signoret, V." box="[573,736,1502,1529]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" pagination="289 - 291" refId="ref13706" refString="Signoret, V. (1850) Description d'un genre nouveau de l'ordre des Hemipteres Heteropteres, et de la section des Hydrocoryses. Revue et magasin de zoologie pure et appliquee, 2, 289 - 291." type="journal article" year="1850">Signoret 1850</bibRefCitation>
) is translated to English as follows: Generally brown. Below a little lighter. Yellowish head and beak, as well as antennae and legs. Granular head and prothorax, very flat, and lateral margins of the latter crenulate. Elytra flattened, finely granulate, and extending over the body below.Anterior femora granular and browner than the insect; the posterior femora yellowish, as well as the tibia. Length 0, 011; width 1, 006. In a redescription, the size was reported as 
<quantity box="[789,889,1646,1673]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.02" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="10.2">10.2 mm</quantity>
length and 
<quantity box="[1020,1085,1646,1673]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
width (
<bibRefCitation author="Montandon, A. L." box="[1170,1368,1646,1672]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" pagination="6 - 23" refId="ref13311" refString="Montandon, A. L. (1897) Hemiptera Cryptocerata. Fam. Naucoridae. - Sous-fam. Cryptocricinae. Verhandlungen der Kaiserlich-Koniglichen Zoologische-Botanischen Gesellschaft in Wien, 47, 6 - 23." type="journal article" year="1897">Montandon 1897</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1214,2033]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">
In a comparison with macropterous 
<taxonomicName authority=", Montandon (1911)" authorityName=", Montandon" authorityYear="1911" box="[616,975,1682,1709]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryphocricos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breddini">
<emphasis box="[616,746,1682,1709]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">C. breddini</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Montandon, A. L." box="[762,975,1682,1708]" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" pagination="83 - 94" refId="ref13346" refString="Montandon, A. L. (1911) Nouvelles especes d'Hydrocorises appartenant aux collections du Museum Entomologique de Berlin. Bulletin de la Societe Roumanie des Sciences, 20 (1), 83 - 94." type="journal article" year="1911">Montandon (1911)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
provided features to distinguish it from brachypterous 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1850" box="[317,439,1718,1745]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryphocricos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barozzii">
<emphasis box="[317,439,1718,1745]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">C. barozzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; however, most of these features are related to differences between wing morphs and are not necessarily interspecific differences. At the time, these were the only two species described; thus, because these features are fairly ubiquitous they are of little use to distinguish among the species currently described. He also reported both species to be of nearly identical size and color.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1214,2033]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,151,429]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="76" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">
After examining thousands of specimens of the genus, I have discovered a feature apparently unique to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1850" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryphocricos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barozzii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">C. barozzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The dark tuberculation of the abdominal terga in brachypterous specimens tends to be sparse and limited to the anterior terga (
<figureCitation box="[316,425,1934,1960]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1036,1060]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,342,1010]" captionTargetId="figure-85@3.[151,1435,342,1010]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Cryphocricos barozzii (1) holotype, (2) brachypterous female from Rosario River, Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil, (3) abdominal terga showing dark tubercles near middle of III–V, (4) subgenital plate of two specimens from Nova Teutonia, Brazil showing intrapopulational variation in shape of posterior margin. Figure 1 courtesy of NHMW Hemiptera Image Collection / Harald Bruckner and Herbert Zettel." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4693075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4693075/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="75">Figs. 2–3</figureCitation>
). More specifically, the tubercles are only on terga III and IV and sometimes a few appear in the paramedian areas of tergum V (anteriorly on fused tergum V of males). On some specimens, the tubercles appear only on the median halves of terga III and IV, whereas on others the tubercles are distributed further laterally. The abdominal tubercle condition of the 
<typeStatus box="[615,713,151,177]" pageId="4" pageNumber="76">holotype</typeStatus>
was confirmed by Herbert Zettel (pers. comm.). The restriction of the abdominal tubercles anteriorly is distinct and appears to be diagnostic for this species, and is clearly different than the condition of other species in which the abdomen is usually either devoid of, or covered with, tubercles. The female subgenital plate exhibits a moderate amount of variation in the shape of the posterior margin; the rounded posterolateral lobes are sometimes well-developed and an incipient medial lobe also can be present (
<figureCitation box="[1280,1350,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–4" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1036,1060]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,342,1010]" captionTargetId="figure-85@3.[151,1435,342,1010]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–4. Cryphocricos barozzii (1) holotype, (2) brachypterous female from Rosario River, Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil, (3) abdominal terga showing dark tubercles near middle of III–V, (4) subgenital plate of two specimens from Nova Teutonia, Brazil showing intrapopulational variation in shape of posterior margin. Figure 1 courtesy of NHMW Hemiptera Image Collection / Harald Bruckner and Herbert Zettel." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4693075" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4693075/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="76">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Many museum collections hold Fritz Plaumann specimens from Nova Teutonia, 
<collectingCountry box="[987,1058,331,357]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="76">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and I have a series from Rosario River in 
<collectingRegion box="[247,458,367,393]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="4" pageNumber="76">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
; these are all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1850" box="[606,727,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryphocricos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barozzii">
<emphasis box="[606,727,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="76">C. barozzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Based on the newly discovered abdominal tubercle feature, the distribution of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Signoret" authorityYear="1850" box="[318,439,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Naucoridae" genus="Cryphocricos" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="76" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="barozzii">
<emphasis box="[318,439,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="76">C. barozzii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes 
<collectingRegion box="[547,711,403,429]" country="Brazil" name="Santa Catarina" pageId="4" pageNumber="76">Santa Catarina</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[765,974,403,429]" country="Brazil" name="Rio Grande do Sul" pageId="4" pageNumber="76">Rio Grande do Sul</collectingRegion>
in the extreme south of 
<collectingCountry box="[1247,1319,403,429]" name="Brazil" pageId="4" pageNumber="76">Brazil</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
